      <section>
        <p>The two teams of PPMG "Acad. Ivan Tsenov" — composed of eleventh-grade students — won the ENEN Secondary School Competition 2025, held from July 14 to 17 in Bologna, Italy. The champions received a crystal cup, a plaque and a cash prize of €1,500.</p>

        <div class="img-grid" aria-hidden="false">
          <img src="../assets/img/stem/bologna_enen-2.jpg" alt="Award ceremony in Bologna" class="img-fluid rounded shadow mb-3" />
          <img src="../assets/img/stem/bologna_enen-3.jpg" alt="Team presentation during ENEN 2025" class="img-fluid rounded shadow mb-3" />
          <img src="../assets/img/stem/bologna_enen-4.jpg" alt="Winners on stage with trophy" class="img-fluid rounded shadow mb-3" />
        </div>

        <p>The competition initially featured 135 teams from 17 countries. The task required teams to produce a 3–4 minute video demonstrating an application of nuclear science — from energy production and radiation protection to medical technologies and space exploration. The PPMG teams impressed the international jury with clear scientific reasoning, innovative content, and strong English-language presentation skills.</p>

        <p>The teams' projects covered topics such as "Nuclear Forensics" and "Nuclear Technologies Supporting Food Safety, Sustainable Agriculture and Clean Drinking Water."</p>

